```json
PUT /puzzles
{
  "mappings": {
    "properties": {
      "puzzleId":        { "type": "keyword" },
      "name":            { "type": "text" },
      "collectionName":  { "type": "keyword" },
      "numberOfPieces":  { "type": "integer" },
      "width":           { "type": "float" },
      "height":          { "type": "float" },
      "description":     { "type": "text", "analyzer": "standard" }
    }
  }
}
```
`puzzleId` and `collectionName` are `keyword` (exact-match / aggregatable, not tokenized â€” needed later to bucket by collection), `numberOfPieces`/`width`/`height` are numeric types, and `name`/`description` are free-text `text` fields so they are analyzed and full-text searchable.

```json
GET /puzzles/_search
{
  "size": 0,
  "aggs": {
    "by_collection": {
      "terms": {
        "field": "collectionName",
        "size": 100
      }
    }
  }
}
```
`size: 0` suppresses the hit list since only the aggregation result is needed. The `terms` aggregation buckets documents by the (non-analyzed) `collectionName` keyword field and returns, for each bucket, `doc_count` â€” the number of puzzles in that collection.

**Number of collections: 4** â€” `companies`, `images`, `frames`, `puzzles` â€” one per entity, because all the relations among them are either `1:N` with potentially many/unbounded children on the "many" side (`Company Produce Puzzle`, `Image Based Puzzle`) or `N:M` (`Puzzle Fit Frame`), so embedding one inside another would either duplicate data across many parents or grow one document unboundedly. Relations are therefore implemented by **reference** (storing the related `_id`(s), MongoDB's analogue of a foreign key):

```json
// companies
{ "_id": "C1", "name": "PuzzleCo", "address": "...", "phoneNumber": "...", "biography": "..." }

// images
{ "_id": "I1", "title": "Starry Night", "width": 30, "height": 40, "description": "...",
  "artistName": "Vincent", "artistSurname": "van Gogh", "paintingLocation": "Van Gogh Museum" }

// frames
{ "_id": "F1", "width": 50, "height": 70, "material": "wood", "color": "black" }

// puzzles
{ "_id": "P1", "name": "Starry Night 1000pc", "collectionName": "Museum Collection",
  "numberOfPieces": 1000, "width": 50, "height": 70, "description": "...",
  "companyId": "C1",
  "imageId": "I1",
  "frameIds": ["F1", "F2"],
  "productionDate": "1998-06-01" }
```
`puzzles` holds a single `companyId` reference (its producer, `1:1` on the puzzle side of `Produce`), a single `imageId` reference (the image it is `Based` on, also `1:1` on the puzzle side), and a `frameIds` array (the `N:M` `Fit` relationship) referencing the frames that fit it.

```javascript
db.puzzles.aggregate([
  { $match: {
      productionDate: { $gt: ISODate("1995-04-30") },
      numberOfPieces: { $gt: 500 }
  }},
  { $group: { _id: "$companyId", totalPuzzles: { $sum: 1 } } },
  { $match: { totalPuzzles: { $gt: 100 } } }
])
```
The first `$match` filters puzzles produced after 1995-04-30 with more than 500 pieces, `$group` counts them per `companyId`, and the second `$match` (the aggregation-pipeline equivalent of `HAVING`) keeps only companies whose count exceeds 100.

```javascript
db.puzzles.aggregate([
  { $lookup: {
      from: "images",
      localField: "imageId",
      foreignField: "_id",
      as: "image"
  }},
  { $unwind: "$image" },
  { $match: {
      "image.artistName": "Leonardo",
      "image.artistSurname": "da Vinci",
      "image.paintingLocation": "Louvre"
  }},
  { $project: {
      _id: 1,
      name: 1,
      totalFrames: { $size: { $setUnion: ["$frameIds", []] } }
  }},
  { $match: { totalFrames: { $gt: 10 } } }
])
```
`$lookup`+`$unwind` join each puzzle to the (single) image it is based on, `$match` restricts to images that are paintings by "Leonardo da Vinci" located at the "Louvre", `$setUnion` with an empty array de-duplicates `frameIds` before `$size` counts the distinct associated frames, and the final `$match` keeps only puzzles with more than 10 such frames.
